\hypertarget{abstract}{%
\section*{Abstract}\label{abstract}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Abstract}

Large language models (LLMs) are increasingly deployed across education,
research, industry, and policy contexts, yet their domain-specific
knowledge remains uneven and insufficiently quantified. Although many
LLMs are described as general-purpose systems, prior evaluations rely
heavily on aggregate benchmarks or narrowly scoped domain tests that
obscure meaningful variation across academic disciplines. The purpose of
this quantitative, comparative benchmarking study was to systematically
evaluate and rank leading LLMs across 26 Scopus-defined academic fields
using a standardized and statistically rigorous framework. A
quasi-experimental design was employed in which multiple
state-of-the-art LLMs were trained on a balanced corpus of 26,000
undergraduate-level multiple-choice items (1,000 per field) under
deterministic conditions. Model performance was analyzed using
descriptive statistics and comparative analysis, with results reported
at both overall and field-specific levels. Findings indicate that no
evaluated LLM demonstrated uniform performance across all academic
fields, and substantial differences were observed both between models
and across disciplines. Specific models consistently outperformed others
in conceptual and analytical domains, while all models exhibited
performance degradation in specialized or applied fields such as
pharmacology, nursing, and selected health sciences. These results
confirm that aggregate performance scores mask critical domain-level
variability and that model selection decisions should be context- and
discipline-aware. This study presents the first comprehensive,
field-level ranking of LLM knowledge across the full academic spectrum.
It provides a replicable evaluation framework to support informed
adoption, governance, and future research in artificial intelligence
assessment.

\textbf{Keywords:} large language models, benchmark evaluation, domain
knowledge, artificial intelligence assessment, academic disciplines

