\hypertarget{chapter-1-introduction}{%
\section*{Chapter 1: Introduction}\label{chapter-1-introduction}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Chapter 1: Introduction}

Over the last decade, large language models (LLMs) such as GPT-4, Claude
3, Gemini, and LLaMA have revolutionized natural language processing by
achieving near--human--level performance on numerous benchmarks (Brown
et al., 2020; Bubeck et al., 2023; Touvron et al., 2023). These systems
are increasingly integrated into higher education, research, healthcare,
business, and government decision-making. Their ability to generate
coherent text, retrieve domain-specific knowledge, and perform reasoning
across topics positions them as powerful tools for knowledge-intensive
work. Despite their broad adoption, persistent questions remain about
the depth of their expertise in specialized academic fields.

Existing cross-domain benchmarks, such as the Massive Multitask Language
Understanding (MMLU) dataset (Hendrycks et al., 2021), reveal
significant performance gradients across disciplines. While LLMs may
excel in conceptual economics or biomedical summarization, they often
struggle in fields that require applied reasoning, such as pharmacology,
physics, or nursing (Kung et al., 2023; Terwiesch, 2023; Wang et al.,
2023). This unevenness raises concerns about deploying LLMs in contexts
where reliability is critical. Without systematic, field-level
evaluation, organizations risk misapplication that may compromise
research integrity, professional outcomes, or public trust. This
dissertation addresses that gap by conducting the first comprehensive,
statistically rigorous ranking of leading LLMs across 26 academic
fields.

\hypertarget{background-of-study}{%
\subsection*{Background of Study}\label{background-of-study}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Background of Study}

LLMs have rapidly advanced through scaling laws and transformer
architectures, demonstrating emergent reasoning capabilities as the
number of parameters and training data increase (Vaswani et al., 2017;
Kaplan et al., 2020). However, most prior evaluations have focused on
single domains, such as medicine (Kung et al., 2023), law (Katz et al.,
2023), or economics (Geerling et al., 2023). Early cross-domain
benchmarks, such as MMLU, highlighted inconsistencies but lacked
coverage across the full range of academic disciplines.

Recent domain-specific efforts include CS-Bench for computer science
(Song et al., 2024), BrainBench for neuroscience (Luo et al., 2024), and
MaScQA for metallurgy (Bajan \& Lambard, 2025). These studies confirm
that performance varies dramatically across domains, but none provide a
unified, field-level comparison across the 26 Scopus-defined fields.
Universities, enterprises, and policymakers therefore lack reliable
evidence when selecting models for specialized applications.

\hypertarget{problem-statement}{%
\subsection*{Problem Statement}\label{problem-statement}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Problem Statement}

The problem this study addresses is that contemporary large language
models (LLMs) demonstrate uneven and insufficiently quantified knowledge
across the 26 major academic fields. At the same time, stakeholders lack
empirically validated, field-level rankings to guide adoption,
governance, and risk management decisions. Although leading LLMs are
frequently described as ``general-purpose'' or ``broadly intelligent,''
existing evidence suggests that their performance varies substantially
depending on the disciplinary context in which they are applied.

Current evaluation practices rely heavily on aggregate benchmarks or
narrowly scoped, domain-specific tests that do not provide a
comprehensive picture of cross-disciplinary capability. For example,
leaderboard-style assessments often report a single overall score,
thereby masking significant differences across fields such as medicine,
economics, mathematics, and pharmacology. Empirical studies have shown
that models like GPT-4 can achieve exceptionally high performance on
business and economics examinations, yet perform below passing
thresholds on professional licensing or clinically oriented assessments
(Wang et al., 2023; Terwiesch, 2023). Without systematic, field-level
comparisons, these disparities remain poorly understood and difficult to
interpret.

This lack of granular benchmarking impacts multiple stakeholder groups.
Universities increasingly rely on LLMs for instructional support,
assessment design, and academic advising, yet lack evidence-based
guidance on whether a given model is appropriate for specific
disciplines. Enterprises and research organizations deploy LLMs for
domain-sensitive tasks such as technical analysis, regulatory
interpretation, and scientific synthesis, often assuming consistent
competence across fields. Policymakers and regulators face additional
challenges, as uneven domain performance may amplify misinformation,
bias, or overconfidence in high-stakes contexts such as healthcare,
finance, or public policy.

What remains unknown is how leading LLMs compare systematically across
all 26 academic fields using a standardized, statistically rigorous
evaluation framework. In the absence of such evidence, organizations
risk deploying models that underperform in specialized domains,
potentially compromising research validity, educational quality,
decision accuracy, and public trust. Addressing this problem requires a
comprehensive, cross-disciplinary evaluation that produces transparent,
field-level rankings and quantifies variability in LLM knowledge. This
study seeks to fill that gap by providing an empirically grounded
comparison of LLM performance across the full spectrum of academic
disciplines.

\hypertarget{purpose-of-dissertation-study}{%
\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{Purpose of Dissertation Study
}{Purpose of Dissertation Study }}\label{purpose-of-dissertation-study}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Purpose of Dissertation Study }

The purpose of this quantitative, comparative benchmarking study is to
evaluate and rank leading LLMs across 26 academic fields. Using a
balanced corpus of 1,000 multiple-choice items per field (26,000 total),
this study will statistically analyze performance differences using
repeated-measures ANOVA and related tests. The results will produce an
Elo-style leaderboard that extends crowdsourced pairwise rankings, such
as those in LMSYS Chatbot Arena, into a comprehensive, field-level
evaluation.

\hypertarget{significance-of-the-study}{%
\subsection*{Significance of the
Study}\label{significance-of-the-study}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Significance of the Study}

This study contributes to scholarship, practice, and policy by:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Advancing scholarship: Extending single-domain benchmarks into a
  systematic, cross-disciplinary evaluation.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Guiding practice: Helping universities, publishers, and R\&D labs
  select models best suited to subject-matter tasks.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Informing policy: Providing regulators with empirical evidence of
  domain gaps that may amplify misinformation or inequities (Bommasani
  et al., 2023).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

By producing the first validated, field-granular leaderboard, this
dissertation addresses a critical knowledge gap and establishes a
replicable standard for future LLM evaluations.

\hypertarget{nature-of-study}{%
\subsection*{Nature of Study}\label{nature-of-study}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Nature of Study}

This research employs a quasi-experimental between-subjects design. Five
to seven state-of-the-art LLMs (e.g., GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini 1.5, LLaMA
3, Phi-3 Mini) will complete the same 26 × 1,000-item corpus under
deterministic temperature-0 settings. Correct answers receive +0.1,
incorrect --0.1, and abstentions 0, ensuring calibrated scoring.
Performance will be analyzed using a repeated-measures ANOVA with Tukey
HSD post hoc tests, along with reliability checks such as bootstrap and
split-half validation. Results will be aggregated into an Elo-style
ranking to highlight domain-specific strengths and weaknesses.

\hypertarget{research-questions-and-hypotheses}{%
\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{Research Questions and Hypotheses
}{Research Questions and Hypotheses }}\label{research-questions-and-hypotheses}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Research Questions and Hypotheses }

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  RQ 1 -- Consistency Across Academic Fields
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\begin{quote}
Research Question: Do any current large-language models (LLMs) exhibit
statistically uniform performance across the 26 academic fields under
study?

Null Hypothesis (H0₁): No current LLM shows uniform performance; for
every model, mean scores differ significantly from one field to another.

(Implied H1₁: At least one LLM's mean scores do not differ significantly
across fields, indicating consistent performance.)
\end{quote}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  RQ 2 -- Between-Model Performance Differences
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\begin{quote}
Research Question: Do current LLMs differ in their mean reasoning
accuracy when processing specialized academic abstracts and research
findings?

Null Hypothesis (H0₂): There is no statistically significant difference
in mean reasoning accuracy among the LLMs on the specialized academic
corpus.

(Implied H1₂: At least one LLM's mean reasoning accuracy differs
significantly from the others.)
\end{quote}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  RQ 3 -- Robustness of Validation Methods
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\begin{quote}
Research Question: Do alternative statistical validation methods yield
different reliability or repeatability estimates for LLM evaluation
results?

Null Hypothesis (H0₃): Reliability and repeatability estimates obtained
from the various validation methods (e.g., split-half, Cronbach's α,
intraclass correlation) do not differ significantly from one another.

(Implied H1₃: At least one validation method produces reliability or
repeatability estimates that differ significantly from those of other
methods.)
\end{quote}

\hypertarget{conceptual-or-theoretical-framework}{%
\subsection*{Conceptual or Theoretical
Framework}\label{conceptual-or-theoretical-framework}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Conceptual or Theoretical Framework}

This study is grounded in the Holistic Evaluation of Language Models
(HELM) framework, which emphasizes accuracy, calibration, robustness,
and fairness (Liang et al., 2022). By applying HELM's ``scenario ×
metric'' lens, the study focuses on accuracy and robustness across
subject domains. Cognitive Load Theory offers an additional perspective,
suggesting that retrieving domain-specific knowledge places variable
demands on working memory, thereby explaining uneven performance across
fields (Bommasani et al., 2023). Together, these frameworks guide the
interpretation of results and situate this research within broader
discussions of model evaluation.

\hypertarget{definitions}{%
\subsection*{Definitions}\label{definitions}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Definitions}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Elo Ranking: A statistical rating system initially designed for chess,
  adapted here to measure relative performance among LLMs by pairwise
  comparisons (Originality.ai, 2024).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Large Language Model (LLM): A transformer-based neural network with
  billions of parameters, pretrained on extensive corpora to generate
  coherent natural language (Brown et al., 2020).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  MMLU Benchmark: A 57-subject multiple-choice dataset widely used to
  evaluate multitask reasoning across academic fields (Hendrycks et al.,
  2021).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{scope-limitations-and-delimitations}{%
\subsection*{Scope, Limitations, and
Delimitations}\label{scope-limitations-and-delimitations}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Scope, Limitations, and Delimitations}

Scope: The study covers 26 Scopus-defined academic fields and uses
English-language, undergraduate-level, multiple-choice items.\\
Limitations: Excludes multimodal reasoning, graduate-level complexity,
and potential biases from prompt formatting or training corpora.\\
Delimitations: Focused on transformer-based models released before April
2025 and excludes smaller or domain-restricted models to preserve
comparability.

\hypertarget{assumptions}{%
\subsection*{Assumptions}\label{assumptions}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Assumptions}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Publicly available model checkpoints approximate the behavior of
  proprietary APIs.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Multiple-choice items sampled from prior exams adequately represent
  domain knowledge.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Deterministic evaluation ensures replicability across runs.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{chapter-summary}{%
\subsection*{Chapter Summary}\label{chapter-summary}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Chapter Summary}

This chapter introduces the study's context, identifies the problem of
uneven LLM performance across academic fields, and articulates the
purpose of a quantitative benchmarking study. The conceptual framework
integrates HELM and Cognitive Load Theory to guide evaluation. Research
questions, scope, limitations, and assumptions were defined to establish
methodological clarity. Chapter 2 will review the literature,
synthesizing existing benchmarks and domain-specific findings to
highlight gaps that this dissertation addresses.

\hypertarget{chapter-2-literature-review}{%
\section*{Chapter 2: Literature
Review}\label{chapter-2-literature-review}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Chapter 2: Literature Review}

\hypertarget{introduction}{%
\subsection*{Introduction}\label{introduction}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Introduction}

This chapter presents a comprehensive literature review relevant to the
proposed study. The purpose of this dissertation is to systematically
evaluate and rank the domain knowledge of state-of-the-art large
language models (LLMs) across 26 academic fields. While prior research
has highlighted impressive LLM performance in specific contexts,
evidence consistently demonstrates uneven results across domains.
Universities, enterprises, and policymakers lack reliable field-level
benchmarks to guide adoption and governance.

The review is organized according to the 26 academic fields defined by
Scopus, in the prescribed order. Each subsection synthesizes existing
research, identifies strengths and weaknesses, and highlights gaps in
the literature. The chapter begins with the theoretical and conceptual
framework underpinning LLM evaluation, followed by a review of
cross-domain benchmarks. It then examines the literature field by field,
culminating in a synthesis of convergence, divergence, and remaining
gaps that justify the present study.

\hypertarget{theoretical-and-conceptual-frameworks-for-evaluating-large-language-models}{%
\subsection*{Theoretical and Conceptual Frameworks for Evaluating Large
Language
Models}\label{theoretical-and-conceptual-frameworks-for-evaluating-large-language-models}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Theoretical and Conceptual Frameworks
for Evaluating Large Language Models}

\hypertarget{holistic-evaluation-of-language-models-helm}{%
\subsubsection*{Holistic Evaluation of Language Models
(HELM)}\label{holistic-evaluation-of-language-models-helm}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Holistic Evaluation of Language
Models (HELM)}

Evaluating large language models (LLMs) requires a structured framework
that accounts for both the technical and cognitive dimensions of
performance. One dominant framework is the Holistic Evaluation of
Language Models (HELM), which emphasizes accuracy, calibration,
robustness, and fairness.

\hypertarget{cognitive-load-theory-and-domain-specific-knowledge}{%
\subsubsection*{Cognitive Load Theory and Domain-Specific
Knowledge}\label{cognitive-load-theory-and-domain-specific-knowledge}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Cognitive Load Theory and
Domain-Specific Knowledge}

Cognitive Load Theory (CLT) helps explain uneven inter-field performance
by considering the load on model memory during domain-specific tasks.
Together, HELM and CLT guide the present study.

\hypertarget{cross-domain-evaluation-of-large-language-models}{%
\subsection*{Cross-Domain Evaluation of Large Language
Models}\label{cross-domain-evaluation-of-large-language-models}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Cross-Domain Evaluation of Large
Language Models}

\hypertarget{general-purpose-benchmarks-and-aggregate-leaderboards}{%
\subsubsection*{General-Purpose Benchmarks and Aggregate
Leaderboards}\label{general-purpose-benchmarks-and-aggregate-leaderboards}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{General-Purpose Benchmarks and
Aggregate Leaderboards}

Cross-domain benchmarks, such as the Massive Multitask Language
Understanding (MMLU) dataset and crowdsourced leaderboards like Chatbot
Arena, demonstrate the broad potential of LLMs but reveal uneven
accuracy across different disciplines.

\hypertarget{limitations-of-single-score-evaluations}{%
\subsubsection*{Limitations of Single-Score
Evaluations}\label{limitations-of-single-score-evaluations}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Limitations of Single-Score
Evaluations}

Studies show that while GPT-4 may excel in economics or general
reasoning, it underperforms in specialized fields like pharmacology.
Domain-specific benchmarks (e.g., CS-Bench, BrainBench, MaScQA) further
highlight this fragmentation.

\hypertarget{need-for-field-level-benchmarking}{%
\subsubsection*{Need for Field-Level
Benchmarking}\label{need-for-field-level-benchmarking}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Need for Field-Level Benchmarking}

Despite significant progress, no empirical study has yet provided a
comprehensive, validated ranking of LLMs across all 26 fields --- a gap
that this dissertation aims to address.

\hypertarget{discipline-specific-evaluations-of-llm-knowledge}{%
\subsection*{Discipline-Specific Evaluations of LLM
Knowledge}\label{discipline-specific-evaluations-of-llm-knowledge}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Discipline-Specific Evaluations of LLM
Knowledge}

\hypertarget{agricultural-and-biological-sciences}{%
\subsubsection*{Agricultural and Biological
Sciences}\label{agricultural-and-biological-sciences}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Agricultural and Biological
Sciences}

Agricultural and biological sciences highlight both the promise and
risks of LLMs. Tzachor et al. (2023) demonstrated that GPT models can
enhance agrarian extension services by simplifying complex research
outputs, but also cautioned about the dangers of misinformation. Lam,
Ong, and Mutwil (2024) found that LLMs facilitate modeling of DNA and
protein sequences, although general-purpose models often lack biological
precision. Specialized models, such as PLLaMa (Yang et al., 2024) and
IPM-AgriGPT (Wang, Li, \& Zhang, 2024), outperform general-purpose
baselines. However, De Clercq et al. (2024) warn against overreliance in
the absence of governance structures. Despite advances, no empirical
comparison situates agricultural performance relative to other academic
fields, a gap this dissertation addresses.

Agricultural sciences show promise in extension services, genomics, and
pest management, with models like PLLaMa and IPM-AgriGPT outperforming
general-purpose LLMs. Yet, risks of misinformation and lack of
cross-field ranking remain.

\hypertarget{arts-and-humanities}{%
\subsubsection*{Arts and Humanities}\label{arts-and-humanities}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Arts and Humanities}

In the arts and humanities, LLMs show promise for supporting
interpretation and research, but they remain limited in depth and
reliability. Doe and Brown (2023) found that models could identify
literary themes but struggled with symbolic analysis. Gonzalez Garcia
and Weilbach (2023) demonstrated that LLMs aid historians in analyzing
primary and secondary documents, although the factual reliability of
these tools is questionable. Gu et al. (2025) demonstrated the strong
performance of DeepSeek-R1 in student writing, while Liu, Wang, Xie, and
Pei (2024) highlighted transformations in digital humanities, including
the preservation of cultural heritage. However, no quantitative
evaluation ranks LLMs across the humanities, underscoring the need for
comparative benchmarks.

Studies demonstrate the utility of LLMs in literary analysis, history,
and digital humanities. While helpful in annotation and interpretation,
reliability and depth remain limited, with no cross-field benchmarks.

\hypertarget{biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology}{%
\subsubsection*{Biochemistry, Genetics, and Molecular
Biology}\label{biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Biochemistry, Genetics, and
Molecular Biology}

LLMs are increasingly applied in biochemistry, genetics, and molecular
biology to accelerate research and discovery. Liu et al. (2024) reviewed
bioinformatics applications and found that models can process complex
datasets in genomics, proteomics, and transcriptomics. Tripathi and
Gabriel (2024) argued that LLMs are reshaping molecular biology by
supporting the discovery of biomarkers and drug development. Feng,
Zhang, and Liu (2024) emphasized that fine-tuning and prompt engineering
enable LLMs to handle protein structure prediction and molecular
property analysis. Zhang et al. (2024) surveyed scientific LLMs across
biology and chemistry, identifying a lack of standardized benchmarks,
while Yin et al. (2024) showed that LLMs excel at entity recognition but
struggle in tasks such as antimicrobial peptide prediction and molecular
optimization. Reliability remains a barrier, as Mugaanyi et al. (2024)
documented hallucinated citations in biomedical writing. Despite
promising research applications, no systematic evaluation has compared
LLM performance in molecular biologywith that in other disciplines.

Applications span genomics, proteomics, and drug discovery. LLMs aid in
biomolecular modeling, but challenges related to hallucination and
reproducibility persist. Cross-field comparisons are absent.

\hypertarget{business-management-and-accounting}{%
\subsubsection*{Business, Management, and
Accounting}\label{business-management-and-accounting}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Business, Management, and
Accounting}

Business-related fields illustrate LLM strengths in conceptual reasoning
and weaknesses in quantitative problem-solving. Wood et al. (2023)
evaluated ChatGPT on 25,000 accounting questions from 186 universities
and found that it consistently underperformed students, especially on
calculation-heavy tasks. Conversely, Geerling, Mateer, and Damodaran
(2023) reported that ChatGPT scored in the 91st percentile in
microeconomics and the 99th percentile in macroeconomics. Fatouros et
al. (2023) showed strong performance in sentiment analysis for finance,
although reliability issues arose due to hallucinations. Rahimikia and
Drinkall (2024) noted that domain-specific financial models outperformed
general-purpose LLMs in return prediction tasks. Yoo (2024) warned that
self-reported confidence scores do not reliably indicate accuracy.

LLMs excel in economic reasoning but struggle with accounting and
quantitative tasks. Reliability concerns in finance remain unresolved
without integrated evaluations.

\hypertarget{chemical-engineering}{%
\subsubsection*{Chemical Engineering}\label{chemical-engineering}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Chemical Engineering}

Chemical engineering highlights the integration of LLMs in process
optimization and autonomous experimentation. Nguyen and Zhao (2024)
optimized reaction conditions and catalyst selection. Gomes et al.
(2023) introduced \emph{Coscientist}, integrating LLMs with laboratory
automation. Zhou et al. (2025) improved prediction accuracy using
chain-of-thought reasoning. Bran et al. (2024) emphasized ChemCrow's
role, though hallucinations remain an issue. Dataset limitations
restrict generalizability.

LLMs support process optimization and autonomous chemical research, but
benchmarks remain fragmented and lack cross-field integration.

\hypertarget{chemistry}{%
\subsubsection*{Chemistry}\label{chemistry}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Chemistry}

In chemistry, LLMs have been tested in symbolic reasoning, synthesis
planning, and chemical interpretation. Guo et al. (2023) found
competence in conceptual descriptions but weaknesses in multi-step
calculations. Tool-augmented approaches such as ChemCrow improve
outcomes. Clinical dentistry-related chemistry tasks show persistent
inaccuracies.

LLMs demonstrate utility in symbolic reasoning and synthesis, but
symbolic manipulation remains a weak point.

\hypertarget{computer-science}{%
\subsubsection*{Computer Science}\label{computer-science}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Computer Science}

Computer science serves as both the foundation for LLM development and a
key testing ground. CS-Bench (Song et al., 2024) shows strong
theoretical performance but weaknesses in applied coding and debugging.
Hou et al. (2023) reviewed 395 papers highlighting scalability issues.
Ellis and Slade (2023) emphasized productivity with continued human
oversight.

Comparative cross-field evaluations remain absent.

\hypertarget{decision-sciences}{%
\subsubsection*{Decision Sciences}\label{decision-sciences}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Decision Sciences}

Decision sciences emphasize reasoning under uncertainty and
explainability. Frameworks such as DeLLMa and ArgLLMs improve
transparency and contestability. Applications remain experimental.

Integration into multi-domain evaluations is needed.

\hypertarget{earth-and-planetary-sciences}{%
\subsubsection*{Earth and Planetary
Sciences}\label{earth-and-planetary-sciences}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Earth and Planetary Sciences}

Earth sciences adopt LLMs for multimodal data analysis and geoscience
modeling. Models like K2 outperform general-purpose baselines, but
reproducibility and interpretability challenges persist.

No comparative benchmarks exist.

\hypertarget{economics-econometrics-and-finance}{%
\subsubsection*{Economics, Econometrics, and
Finance}\label{economics-econometrics-and-finance}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Economics, Econometrics, and
Finance}

GPT-4 excels in economics exams. Forecasting and financial analysis show
mixed results. Reliability issues and confidence miscalibration persist.

Comparative evaluations across disciplines are lacking.

\hypertarget{energy}{%
\subsubsection*{Energy}\label{energy}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Energy}

LLMs support forecasting, regulatory parsing, and energy system
optimization. Models like EF-LLM reduce hallucinations. Proprietary
datasets limit reproducibility.

\hypertarget{engineering}{%
\subsubsection*{Engineering}\label{engineering}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Engineering}

Engineering fields integrate LLMs in automation, debugging, and
modeling. Productivity improves, but applied reasoning remains weak.

Systematic cross-field evaluations are needed.

\hypertarget{environmental-science}{%
\subsubsection*{Environmental Science}\label{environmental-science}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Environmental Science}

LLMs aid climate research and opportunity discovery but raise concerns
about ethical and environmental costs. EnviroExam reveals uneven
performance.

Comparative benchmarks are lacking.

\hypertarget{immunology-and-microbiology}{%
\subsubsection*{Immunology and
Microbiology}\label{immunology-and-microbiology}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Immunology and Microbiology}

LLMs underperform on infectious disease exams. Protein language models
improve receptor modeling. Reliability and interpretability remain
issues.

\hypertarget{materials-science}{%
\subsubsection*{Materials Science}\label{materials-science}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Materials Science}

Proprietary models dominate benchmarks like MaScQA. Domain-specific
models outperform open-source LLMs. Cross-field integration is absent.

\hypertarget{mathematics}{%
\subsubsection*{Mathematics}\label{mathematics}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Mathematics}

LLMs struggle with symbolic reasoning. Models like Llemma and ToRA
improve outcomes but lack comparative evaluations.

\hypertarget{medicine}{%
\subsubsection*{Medicine}\label{medicine}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Medicine}

LLMs approach or surpass human performance in some benchmarks, but face
hallucination and ethical risks. No cross-field evaluation exists.

\hypertarget{neuroscience}{%
\subsubsection*{Neuroscience}\label{neuroscience}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Neuroscience}

BrainBench shows LLMs outperform experts in forecasting.
Interpretability remains limited.

\hypertarget{nursing}{%
\subsubsection*{Nursing}\label{nursing}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Nursing}

LLMs near passing thresholds on exams but struggle in pharmacology.
Reliability concerns persist.

\hypertarget{pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutics}{%
\subsubsection*{Pharmacology, Toxicology, and
Pharmaceutics}\label{pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutics}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Pharmacology, Toxicology, and
Pharmaceutics}

LLMs underperform on licensing exams. Domain-specific agents show
promise.

\hypertarget{physics-and-astronomy}{%
\subsubsection*{Physics and Astronomy}\label{physics-and-astronomy}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Physics and Astronomy}

Conceptual reasoning outperforms quantitative problem-solving.
Reinforcement approaches improve accuracy.

\hypertarget{psychology}{%
\subsubsection*{Psychology}\label{psychology}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Psychology}

LLMs exhibit emergent theory-of-mind reasoning but remain brittle.

\hypertarget{social-sciences}{%
\subsubsection*{Social Sciences}\label{social-sciences}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Social Sciences}

LLMs scale annotation and simulation, but face validity risks.

\hypertarget{dentistry}{%
\subsubsection*{Dentistry}\label{dentistry}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Dentistry}

GPT-4 outperforms peers but produces vague responses. Multimodal models
show promise.

\hypertarget{health-professions}{%
\subsubsection*{Health Professions}\label{health-professions}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Health Professions}

LLMs support education and diagnostics. Ethical and governance issues
persist.

\hypertarget{synthesis-of-literature-across-academic-fields}{%
\subsection*{Synthesis of Literature Across Academic
Fields}\label{synthesis-of-literature-across-academic-fields}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Synthesis of Literature Across
Academic Fields}

\hypertarget{areas-of-convergence-and-divergence}{%
\subsubsection*{Areas of Convergence and
Divergence}\label{areas-of-convergence-and-divergence}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Areas of Convergence and
Divergence}

Across the 26 academic fields, specialized models outperform
general-purpose LLMs. Performance is strongest in conceptual reasoning
and weakest in applied, high-stakes contexts. Tool-augmented systems
improve reliability.

\hypertarget{gaps-in-the-literature}{%
\subsubsection*{Gaps in the Literature}\label{gaps-in-the-literature}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Gaps in the Literature}

No comprehensive study ranks LLM knowledge across all 26 academic
fields. Existing benchmarks lack either breadth or comparability.

\hypertarget{chapter-summary-1}{%
\subsection*{Chapter Summary}\label{chapter-summary-1}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Chapter Summary}

This chapter reviewed the literature on LLM evaluation across 26
academic fields, identifying converging strengths, divergent approaches,
and critical gaps. These findings justify the present study's purpose:
producing the first comprehensive, field-level ranking of LLM knowledge.
The next chapter presents the methodology used to achieve this goal.

\hypertarget{chapter-3-methodology}{%
\section*{Chapter 3: Methodology}\label{chapter-3-methodology}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Chapter 3: Methodology}

\textbf{Introduction}

This chapter outlines the methodology employed in the study. The problem
addressed is that current large language models (LLMs) demonstrate
uneven and insufficiently quantified knowledge across the 26 major
academic fields, leaving stakeholders without validated benchmarks for
adoption and governance The purpose of this quantitative, comparative
evaluation study is to rank the domain knowledge of state-of-the-art
LLMs across 26 academic fields by administering a balanced corpus of
multiple-choice items and statistically analyzing differences in mean
accurac. This chapter describes the research design, population and
sample, instruments, procedures, data analysis, and ethical
considerations, providing a roadmap for replication. The end-to-end
evaluation pipeline used in this study is summarized in
Figure~\ref{fig:methodology-pipeline}, which traces the flow from
question-bank curation through standardized administration, calibrated
scoring, and statistical analysis to the final field-level leaderboard.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{figures/fig3_1_methodology_flowchart.png}
\caption{End-to-end quasi-experimental evaluation pipeline used to rank
LLMs across 26 academic fields. Inputs (blue) feed standardized
administration steps (orange), calibrated scoring and statistical
inference (green), and a final field-level reporting stage (red).}
\label{fig:methodology-pipeline}
\end{figure}

\hypertarget{research-method-and-design-appropriateness}{%
\subsection*{\texorpdfstring{Research Method and Design Appropriateness
}{Research Method and Design Appropriateness }}\label{research-method-and-design-appropriateness}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Research Method and Design
Appropriateness }

A quasi-experimental, between-models design will be employed to compare
the performance of multiple LLMs across 26 fields. Each model (e.g.,
GPT-4, Claude 3 Opus, Gemini 1.5 Pro, LLaMA 3 70B, Phi-3 Mini) will
complete the identical test set of 1,000 multiple-choice items per
field. The independent variable is the LLM used, while the dependent
variable is the accuracy score. Alternative designs, such as case
studies or qualitative interviews, were deemed less appropriate because
they could not provide statistically rigorous, field-level comparisons.

\textbf{Population and Sampling}

The population of interest includes the 26 academic fields defined by
Scopus. The sample will consist of 1,000 multiple-choice items per
field, drawn from prior exams, validated question banks, and
peer-reviewed sources. This results in a total sample of 26,000 items.
The models selected represent widely used, state-of-the-art
transformer-based architectures available as of April 2025. This
sampling approach ensures breadth and depth of domain knowledge while
maintaining replicability.

\hypertarget{data-collection-procedures-and-rationale}{%
\subsection*{Data Collection Procedures and
Rationale}\label{data-collection-procedures-and-rationale}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Data Collection Procedures and
Rationale}

The instrument used is a balanced corpus of multiple-choice items,
standardized to undergraduate-level knowledge. Each item has one correct
answer and three incorrect options, known as distractors. Correct
responses will be scored as +0.1, incorrect responses as -0.1, and
abstentions as 0, in line with best practices for calibrated scoring.
The calibrated scoring schema is illustrated in
Figure~\ref{fig:scoring-schema}, which shows how the asymmetric reward
structure penalizes uninformed guessing while permitting models to
abstain when uncertain. Deterministic evaluation (temperature = 0) will
be applied to eliminate randomness. Items were selected to represent
domain knowledge, and pilot testing will be conducted to ensure fairness
across models.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{figures/fig3_3_scoring_schema.png}
\caption{Calibrated scoring schema for multiple-choice items. Correct
responses receive +0.1, abstentions receive 0, and incorrect responses
receive \(-\)0.1, discouraging random guessing while allowing models to
withhold uncertain answers.}
\label{fig:scoring-schema}
\end{figure}

\hypertarget{validity-and-reliability-internal-and-external}{%
\subsection*{Validity and Reliability: Internal and
External}\label{validity-and-reliability-internal-and-external}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Validity and Reliability: Internal and
External}

Independent Variable: The LLM evaluated (GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini 1.5,
etc.).\\
Dependent Variable: Mean accuracy scores per academic field.\\
Measurement: Accuracy will be calculated as the percentage of correct
responses across 1,000 items per field, adjusted by the scoring schema.
Figure~\ref{fig:variable-framework} summarizes the relationship between
these variables and the controls held constant across model evaluations.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{figures/fig3_2_variable_framework.png}
\caption{Variable framework for the study. The independent variable is
the LLM evaluated; the dependent variable is the mean field-level
calibrated accuracy. Identical item sets, prompt template, deterministic
sampling, and the 26 Scopus fields are held constant as controls.}
\label{fig:variable-framework}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Data Analysis Procedures}

1. Assemble a balanced test corpus (1,000 questions per field).\\
2. Standardize item formatting to ensure consistency.\\
3. Configure deterministic evaluation for each model.\\
4 Administer the test corpus to each LLM under identical conditions.\\
5. Record and score results using the calibrated scoring system. 6.
Compile accuracy scores per field and model for analysis.

Data will be analyzed using a one-way repeated-measures ANOVA to test
for differences in model performance across fields. Tukey's HSD will be
used for post hoc comparisons. Levene's test assesses homogeneity of
variance. Reliability will be evaluated using bootstrap and split-half
validation methods. Statistical significance will be set at p
\textless{} 0.05. Analyses will be conducted using statistical software
(e.g., SPSS, R).

\hypertarget{organization-and-clarity}{%
\subsection*{Organization and Clarity}\label{organization-and-clarity}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Organization and Clarity}

Validity will be supported by constructing the test corpus from
validated sources and piloting items before deployment. Credibility is
enhanced through deterministic evaluation to remove stochastic noise.
Reliability will be examined via multiple validation strategies.
Researcher bias is minimized by automating model evaluation and scoring.

1. Publicly available model checkpoints behave comparably to their
proprietary API versions.\\
2. Multiple-choice items adequately represent domain knowledge in each
field. Deterministic evaluation settings ensure replicable results.

This study is limited by its focus on English-language items at an
undergraduate level, excluding multimodal and higher-order reasoning.
Prompt-format bias and differences in pretraining corpora may influence
outcomes. The study is restricted to transformer-based models released
by April 2025.

Delimitations include limiting the scope to 26 Scopus fields, a
multiple-choice question format, and deterministic evaluation
conditions. These decisions enhance comparability but restrict
generalization to other tasks or languages.

This study involves no human subjects and therefore qualifies for IRB
exemption. All data will be sourced from publicly available sources and
securely stored in accordance with institutional guidelines and
regulations. The researcher acknowledges the potential for bias due to
prior experience with LLM evaluation but will employ strategies such as
blind scoring and external replication to mitigate this risk.

\hypertarget{chapter-summary-2}{%
\subsection*{Chapter Summary}\label{chapter-summary-2}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Chapter Summary}

This chapter detailed the methodology for systematically evaluating LLM
knowledge across 26 academic fields. The design, population,
instruments, and procedures were described in detail, along with
statistical analysis, validity strategies, assumptions, and limitations.
By applying a rigorous and replicable methodology, the study aims to
produce the first comprehensive leaderboard of LLM performance across
academic disciplines. The next chapter will present the results of this
analysis.

\textbf{Chapter 4: Analysis and Results\\
Introduction}

The problem this study addresses is that contemporary large language
models (LLMs) demonstrate uneven and insufficiently quantified knowledge
across the 26 major academic fields. At the same time, stakeholders lack
empirically validated, field-level rankings to guide adoption,
governance, and risk management decisions. Although leading LLMs are
frequently described as ``general-purpose'' or ``broadly intelligent,''
existing evidence suggests that their performance varies substantially
depending on the disciplinary context in which they are applied.\\
\strut \\
The purpose of this quantitative, comparative benchmarking study is to
evaluate and rank leading LLMs across 26 academic fields. Using a
balanced corpus of 1,000 multiple-choice items per field (26,000 total),
this study will statistically analyze performance differences using
repeated-measures ANOVA and related tests. The results will produce an
Elo-style leaderboard that extends crowdsourced pairwise rankings, such
as those in LMSYS Chatbot Arena, into a comprehensive, field-level
evaluation.\\
\strut \\
This chapter reports the outcomes of the pilot study and the primary
evaluation. Across both phases, results show substantial variation in
model performance by academic field, supporting the need for field-level
reporting rather than reliance on single aggregate scores. The chapter
is organized around the study's research questions and presents the
results objectively, consistent with expectations for doctoral
reporting.

\hypertarget{trustworthiness-validity-of-the-data}{%
\subsection*{Trustworthiness (Validity) of the
Data}\label{trustworthiness-validity-of-the-data}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Trustworthiness (Validity) of the
Data}

\hypertarget{trustworthiness-and-validity-were-addressed-through-standardized-instrumentation-and-consistent-execution-conditions-as-described-in-chapter-3.-the-same-response-format-and-scoring-schema-were-applied-to-all-models-and-each-model-was-evaluated-using-the-same-field-structure-and-question-formats-to-ensure-comparability.-in-addition-deterministic-and-controlled-prompting-procedures-were-used-to-reduce-stochastic-variation-attributable-to-sampling-or-response-formatting-in-this-study-contextmachine-generated-outputs-rather-than-human-subjectsthe-instruments-consistency-primarily-supports-validity-the-stability-of-the-evaluation-pipeline-and-the-comparability-of-testing-conditions-across-models.}{%
\section*{Trustworthiness and validity were addressed through
standardized instrumentation and consistent execution conditions as
described in Chapter 3. The same response format and scoring schema were
applied to all models, and each model was evaluated using the same field
structure and question formats to ensure comparability. In addition,
deterministic and controlled prompting procedures were used to reduce
stochastic variation attributable to sampling or response formatting (in
this study context---machine-generated outputs rather than human
subjects---the instrument\textquotesingle s consistency primarily
supports validity, the stability of the evaluation pipeline, and the
comparability of testing conditions across
models).}\label{trustworthiness-and-validity-were-addressed-through-standardized-instrumentation-and-consistent-execution-conditions-as-described-in-chapter-3.-the-same-response-format-and-scoring-schema-were-applied-to-all-models-and-each-model-was-evaluated-using-the-same-field-structure-and-question-formats-to-ensure-comparability.-in-addition-deterministic-and-controlled-prompting-procedures-were-used-to-reduce-stochastic-variation-attributable-to-sampling-or-response-formatting-in-this-study-contextmachine-generated-outputs-rather-than-human-subjectsthe-instruments-consistency-primarily-supports-validity-the-stability-of-the-evaluation-pipeline-and-the-comparability-of-testing-conditions-across-models.}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Trustworthiness and validity were
addressed through standardized instrumentation and consistent execution
conditions as described in Chapter 3. The same response format and
scoring schema were applied to all models, and each model was evaluated
using the same field structure and question formats to ensure
comparability. In addition, deterministic and controlled prompting
procedures were used to reduce stochastic variation attributable to
sampling or response formatting (in this study
context---machine-generated outputs rather than human subjects---the
instrument\textquotesingle s consistency primarily supports validity,
the stability of the evaluation pipeline, and the comparability of
testing conditions across models).}

\hypertarget{pilot-study}{%
\subsection*{Pilot Study}\label{pilot-study}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Pilot Study}

\hypertarget{purpose-and-process}{%
\subsubsection*{Purpose and Process}\label{purpose-and-process}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Purpose and Process}

\hypertarget{a-pilot-study-was-conducted-to-validate-the-end-to-end-evaluation-pipeline-including-a-the-ability-to-load-and-query-field-specific-question-banks-b-the-stability-of-automated-scoring-and-c-the-feasibility-of-benchmarking-many-models-across-26-academic-fields.-the-pilot-phase-evaluated-a-wide-range-of-locally-executed-models-across-the-complete-set-of-academic-fields-producing-preliminary-distributions-of-scores-by-model-and-by-field.-this-pilot-confirmed-that-the-pipeline-could-consistently-generate-and-record-model-level-performance-scores-across-the-whole-domain-taxonomy-before-executing-the-final-api-based-evaluation.}{%
\section*{A pilot study was conducted to validate the end-to-end
evaluation pipeline, including (a) the ability to load and query
field-specific question banks, (b) the stability of automated scoring,
and (c) the feasibility of benchmarking many models across 26 academic
fields. The pilot phase evaluated a wide range of locally executed
models across the complete set of academic fields, producing preliminary
distributions of scores by model and by field. This pilot confirmed that
the pipeline could consistently generate and record model-level
performance scores across the whole domain taxonomy before executing the
final API-based
evaluation.}\label{a-pilot-study-was-conducted-to-validate-the-end-to-end-evaluation-pipeline-including-a-the-ability-to-load-and-query-field-specific-question-banks-b-the-stability-of-automated-scoring-and-c-the-feasibility-of-benchmarking-many-models-across-26-academic-fields.-the-pilot-phase-evaluated-a-wide-range-of-locally-executed-models-across-the-complete-set-of-academic-fields-producing-preliminary-distributions-of-scores-by-model-and-by-field.-this-pilot-confirmed-that-the-pipeline-could-consistently-generate-and-record-model-level-performance-scores-across-the-whole-domain-taxonomy-before-executing-the-final-api-based-evaluation.}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{A pilot study was conducted to validate
the end-to-end evaluation pipeline, including (a) the ability to load
and query field-specific question banks, (b) the stability of automated
scoring, and (c) the feasibility of benchmarking many models across 26
academic fields. The pilot phase evaluated a wide range of locally
executed models across the complete set of academic fields, producing
preliminary distributions of scores by model and by field. This pilot
confirmed that the pipeline could consistently generate and record
model-level performance scores across the whole domain taxonomy before
executing the final API-based evaluation.}

\hypertarget{pilot-results-summary}{%
\subsubsection*{Pilot Results Summary}\label{pilot-results-summary}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsubsection}{Pilot Results Summary}

\hypertarget{the-pilot-results-demonstrate-that-model-performance-varies-substantially-across-model-families-and-parameter-scales-with-several-models-achieving-strong-stable-performance-across-most-fields.-in-contrast-others-produce-near-zero-or-zero-scores-in-the-same-categories.-for-example-multiple-pilot-models-achieved-relatively-high-overall-scores-e.g.-llama27b-89.3308-glm49b-89.25-smollm2135m-88.6654-llama213b-88.0038-llama3.18b-87.05-tinydolphin1.1b-87.1-suggesting-that-several-architectures-can-perform-competitively-across-the-26-field-structure-under-consistent-testing.-by-contrast-multiple-models-produced-overall-values-at-or-near-zero-e.g.-multiple-qwen3-entries-and-multiple-deepseek-r1-entries-indicating-failure-states-incompatibility-or-nonresponsive-behavior-under-the-evaluation-configuration-rather-than-meaningful-domain-knowledge-measurement.-these-pilot-outcomes-supported-proceeding-to-the-primary-evaluation-while-reinforcing-the-importance-of-model-eligibility-checks-and-validation-controls.}{%
\section*{The pilot results demonstrate that model performance varies
substantially across model families and parameter scales, with several
models achieving strong, stable performance across most fields. In
contrast, others produce near-zero or zero scores in the same
categories. For example, multiple pilot models achieved relatively high
overall scores (e.g., llama2:7b = 89.3308, glm4:9b = 89.25, smollm2:135m
= 88.6654, llama2:13b = 88.0038, llama3.1:8b = 87.05, tinydolphin:1.1b =
87.1), suggesting that several architectures can perform competitively
across the 26-field structure under consistent testing. By contrast,
multiple models produced overall values at or near zero (e.g., multiple
``qwen3'' entries and multiple ``deepseek-r1'' entries), indicating
failure states, incompatibility, or nonresponsive behavior under the
evaluation configuration rather than meaningful domain-knowledge
measurement. These pilot outcomes supported proceeding to the primary
evaluation while reinforcing the importance of model eligibility checks
and validation
controls.}\label{the-pilot-results-demonstrate-that-model-performance-varies-substantially-across-model-families-and-parameter-scales-with-several-models-achieving-strong-stable-performance-across-most-fields.-in-contrast-others-produce-near-zero-or-zero-scores-in-the-same-categories.-for-example-multiple-pilot-models-achieved-relatively-high-overall-scores-e.g.-llama27b-89.3308-glm49b-89.25-smollm2135m-88.6654-llama213b-88.0038-llama3.18b-87.05-tinydolphin1.1b-87.1-suggesting-that-several-architectures-can-perform-competitively-across-the-26-field-structure-under-consistent-testing.-by-contrast-multiple-models-produced-overall-values-at-or-near-zero-e.g.-multiple-qwen3-entries-and-multiple-deepseek-r1-entries-indicating-failure-states-incompatibility-or-nonresponsive-behavior-under-the-evaluation-configuration-rather-than-meaningful-domain-knowledge-measurement.-these-pilot-outcomes-supported-proceeding-to-the-primary-evaluation-while-reinforcing-the-importance-of-model-eligibility-checks-and-validation-controls.}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The pilot results demonstrate that model
performance varies substantially across model families and parameter
scales, with several models achieving strong, stable performance across
most fields. In contrast, others produce near-zero or zero scores in the
same categories. For example, multiple pilot models achieved relatively
high overall scores (e.g., llama2:7b = 89.3308, glm4:9b = 89.25,
smollm2:135m = 88.6654, llama2:13b = 88.0038, llama3.1:8b = 87.05,
tinydolphin:1.1b = 87.1), suggesting that several architectures can
perform competitively across the 26-field structure under consistent
testing. By contrast, multiple models produced overall values at or near
zero (e.g., multiple ``qwen3'' entries and multiple ``deepseek-r1''
entries), indicating failure states, incompatibility, or nonresponsive
behavior under the evaluation configuration rather than meaningful
domain-knowledge measurement. These pilot outcomes supported proceeding
to the primary evaluation while reinforcing the importance of model
eligibility checks and validation controls.}

