\hypertarget{the-results-data-provided-in-this-chapter-include-pilot-outputs-and-primary-outputs-but-do-not-by-themselves-include-the-complete-set-of-computed-reliability-statistics-e.g.-split-half-reliability-cronbachs-ux3b1-intraclass-correlation-or-bootstrap-confidence-intervals-as-a-result-this-chapter-reports-the-available-empirical-outputs-and-reserves-formal-reporting-of-reliability-coefficients-for-the-analysis-step-where-those-measures-are-calculated-and-presented.}{%
\section*{The results data provided in this chapter include pilot
outputs and primary outputs, but do not, by themselves, include the
complete set of computed reliability statistics (e.g., split-half
reliability, Cronbach's α, intraclass correlation, or bootstrap
confidence intervals) As a result, this chapter reports the available
empirical outputs and reserves formal reporting of reliability
coefficients for the analysis step where those measures are calculated
and
presented.}\label{the-results-data-provided-in-this-chapter-include-pilot-outputs-and-primary-outputs-but-do-not-by-themselves-include-the-complete-set-of-computed-reliability-statistics-e.g.-split-half-reliability-cronbachs-ux3b1-intraclass-correlation-or-bootstrap-confidence-intervals-as-a-result-this-chapter-reports-the-available-empirical-outputs-and-reserves-formal-reporting-of-reliability-coefficients-for-the-analysis-step-where-those-measures-are-calculated-and-presented.}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{The results data provided in this chapter
include pilot outputs and primary outputs, but do not, by themselves,
include the complete set of computed reliability statistics (e.g.,
split-half reliability, Cronbach's α, intraclass correlation, or
bootstrap confidence intervals) As a result, this chapter reports the
available empirical outputs and reserves formal reporting of reliability
coefficients for the analysis step where those measures are calculated
and presented.}

\hypertarget{however-the-pilot-results-provide-preliminary-evidence-that-repeatability-is-feasible-under-controlled-conditions-multiple-pilot-runs-as-shown-in-the-appended-data-excerpt-display-similar-score-ranges-for-many-models-suggesting-limited-drift-when-the-evaluation-pipeline-and-dataset-remain-stable.-these-observations-support-the-feasibility-of-the-planned-validation-approach-and-motivate-formal-computation-of-reliability-statistics-in-the-next-analytic-step.}{%
\section*{However, the pilot results provide preliminary evidence that
repeatability is feasible under controlled conditions: multiple pilot
runs (as shown in the appended data excerpt) display similar score
ranges for many models, suggesting limited drift when the evaluation
pipeline and dataset remain stable. These observations support the
feasibility of the planned validation approach and motivate formal
computation of reliability statistics in the next analytic
step.}\label{however-the-pilot-results-provide-preliminary-evidence-that-repeatability-is-feasible-under-controlled-conditions-multiple-pilot-runs-as-shown-in-the-appended-data-excerpt-display-similar-score-ranges-for-many-models-suggesting-limited-drift-when-the-evaluation-pipeline-and-dataset-remain-stable.-these-observations-support-the-feasibility-of-the-planned-validation-approach-and-motivate-formal-computation-of-reliability-statistics-in-the-next-analytic-step.}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{However, the pilot results provide
preliminary evidence that repeatability is feasible under controlled
conditions: multiple pilot runs (as shown in the appended data excerpt)
display similar score ranges for many models, suggesting limited drift
when the evaluation pipeline and dataset remain stable. These
observations support the feasibility of the planned validation approach
and motivate formal computation of reliability statistics in the next
analytic step.}

\hypertarget{chapter-summary-3}{%
\subsection*{Chapter Summary}\label{chapter-summary-3}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{subsection}{Chapter Summary}

\hypertarget{this-chapter-presented-the-results-of-the-pilot-study-and-the-primary-evaluation-outcomes-for-ranking-large-language-models-across-26-academic-fields.-consistent-with-the-study-problem-results-show-that-model-performance-is-not-uniform-across-academic-domains-and-that-single-aggregate-scores-conceal-meaningful-field-level-variation.-the-primary-evaluation-also-demonstrates-apparent-between-model-differences-with-openais-model-achieving-the-highest-overall-score-among-the-evaluated-apis.-in-contrast-the-other-models-show-lower-overall-and-field-level-performance-under-the-same-structure.-finally-although-this-chapter-reports-empirical-results-from-the-pilot-and-primary-evaluations-the-planned-reliability-and-robustness-statistics-require-formal-computation-and-reporting-in-the-corresponding-analytic-step.-the-next-chapter-will-interpret-these-results-connect-findings-to-the-literature-and-conceptual-framework-and-provide-recommendations-based-on-the-observed-field-level-performance-patterns.}{%
\section*{This chapter presented the results of the pilot study and the
primary evaluation outcomes for ranking large language models across 26
academic fields. Consistent with the study problem, results show that
model performance is not uniform across academic domains and that single
aggregate scores conceal meaningful field-level variation. The primary
evaluation also demonstrates apparent between-model differences, with
OpenAI's model achieving the highest overall score among the evaluated
APIs. In contrast, the other models show lower overall and field-level
performance under the same structure. Finally, although this chapter
reports empirical results from the pilot and primary evaluations, the
planned reliability and robustness statistics require formal computation
and reporting in the corresponding analytic step. The next chapter will
interpret these results, connect findings to the literature and
conceptual framework, and provide recommendations based on the observed
field-level performance
patterns.}\label{this-chapter-presented-the-results-of-the-pilot-study-and-the-primary-evaluation-outcomes-for-ranking-large-language-models-across-26-academic-fields.-consistent-with-the-study-problem-results-show-that-model-performance-is-not-uniform-across-academic-domains-and-that-single-aggregate-scores-conceal-meaningful-field-level-variation.-the-primary-evaluation-also-demonstrates-apparent-between-model-differences-with-openais-model-achieving-the-highest-overall-score-among-the-evaluated-apis.-in-contrast-the-other-models-show-lower-overall-and-field-level-performance-under-the-same-structure.-finally-although-this-chapter-reports-empirical-results-from-the-pilot-and-primary-evaluations-the-planned-reliability-and-robustness-statistics-require-formal-computation-and-reporting-in-the-corresponding-analytic-step.-the-next-chapter-will-interpret-these-results-connect-findings-to-the-literature-and-conceptual-framework-and-provide-recommendations-based-on-the-observed-field-level-performance-patterns.}}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{This chapter presented the results of the
pilot study and the primary evaluation outcomes for ranking large
language models across 26 academic fields. Consistent with the study
problem, results show that model performance is not uniform across
academic domains and that single aggregate scores conceal meaningful
field-level variation. The primary evaluation also demonstrates apparent
between-model differences, with OpenAI's model achieving the highest
overall score among the evaluated APIs. In contrast, the other models
show lower overall and field-level performance under the same structure.
Finally, although this chapter reports empirical results from the pilot
and primary evaluations, the planned reliability and robustness
statistics require formal computation and reporting in the corresponding
analytic step. The next chapter will interpret these results, connect
findings to the literature and conceptual framework, and provide
recommendations based on the observed field-level performance patterns.}

